WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:05:24.707 --> 00:05:28.940
- So, Sal here at Khan Academy
worldwide headquarters,

00:05:28.940 --> 00:05:31.810
and I'm excited to be
here with Barbara Oakley,

00:05:31.810 --> 00:05:35.250
who's an expert on learning
and learning how to learn.

00:05:35.250 --> 00:05:37.010
And so, Barbara, let me just start

00:05:37.010 --> 00:05:38.750
with a question that I'm sure many that

00:05:38.750 --> 00:05:41.590
many of Khan Academy users or
young people around the world,

00:05:41.590 --> 00:05:43.119
frankly, all people have faced,

00:05:43.119 --> 00:05:45.510
which is you're trying to learn something,

00:05:45.510 --> 00:05:46.790
and you're looking at a textbook

00:05:46.790 --> 00:05:48.670
or a teacher's giving a lecture,

00:05:48.670 --> 00:05:50.290
and all of a sudden it's
just not making sense

00:05:50.290 --> 00:05:52.940
and you keep trying to
pound your head on it.

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:55.190
What's going on in the brain at that time,

00:05:55.190 --> 00:05:58.763
and is the only option to
keep trying to power forward?

00:05:59.611 --> 00:06:01.240
- Oooo, the last thing you want to do

00:06:01.240 --> 00:06:03.120
is keep powering forward.

00:06:03.120 --> 00:06:05.450
I mean, ultimately you want to do that,

00:06:05.450 --> 00:06:08.910
but if you're really stuck,
and you're very frustrated,

00:06:08.910 --> 00:06:10.960
as I used to get, when
I was trying to study

00:06:10.960 --> 00:06:13.250
when I was growing up,
the best thing to do

00:06:13.250 --> 00:06:18.040
is to back off and get
your mind completely off

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:19.160
what you're stuck on.

00:06:19.160 --> 00:06:20.960
And I mean completely off.

00:06:20.960 --> 00:06:23.740
So either study something very different,

00:06:23.740 --> 00:06:26.650
or go out for a walk, or just do something

00:06:26.650 --> 00:06:28.520
that gets your mind off of it.

00:06:28.520 --> 00:06:30.379
As soon as you get your mind off it,

00:06:30.379 --> 00:06:35.040
it turns out, that opens up
a completely different set

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:36.500
of neural circuits.

00:06:36.500 --> 00:06:39.100
It's the difference between task positive,

00:06:39.100 --> 00:06:41.500
where you're focusing, and task negative,

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:43.310
where you're not focusing at all,

00:06:43.310 --> 00:06:46.910
and these other, this
alternate set of circuits

00:06:46.910 --> 00:06:49.550
is what allows you to begin making sense

00:06:49.550 --> 00:06:51.900
of the stuff that you've
been struggling with.

00:06:51.900 --> 00:06:54.950
So as long as you're focusing on it,

00:06:54.950 --> 00:06:57.370
you're actually keeping yourself stuck,

00:06:57.370 --> 00:07:00.480
because you're not allowing
these other neural circuits

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:02.130
to kinda kick into gear.

00:07:02.130 --> 00:07:06.170
So that's why people say, back
off when you get frustrated.

00:07:06.170 --> 00:07:08.760
I never understood that
before and now I do.

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:10.490
It's very powerful.

00:07:10.490 --> 00:07:12.743
- So what you're saying
actually backs up my experience.

00:07:12.743 --> 00:07:14.814
I remember in college
when I used to take these,

00:07:14.814 --> 00:07:18.800
kind of, very difficult
math proof classes,

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:20.860
and these proofs, the
first time you look at 'em,

00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:21.890
I'd be like I don't know,

00:07:21.890 --> 00:07:23.889
but I got into a habit,
I kinda fell into it,

00:07:23.889 --> 00:07:27.030
of I would read the proofs
and make sure I understood,

00:07:27.030 --> 00:07:28.690
or read what I was trying to prove

00:07:28.690 --> 00:07:30.080
and make sure I understood it,

00:07:30.080 --> 00:07:31.043
and then I would go to sleep,

00:07:31.043 --> 00:07:32.980
and then I would wake
up in the next morning,

00:07:32.980 --> 00:07:34.810
and it was like I had just
kinda got out of the work,

00:07:34.810 --> 00:07:36.621
I had delegated it to my brain.

00:07:36.621 --> 00:07:38.240
And it just happened, and you're saying,

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:40.090
that actually is, it's based in science.

00:07:40.090 --> 00:07:42.660
- It's based in really good science.

00:07:42.660 --> 00:07:44.500
In fact there's some great research out

00:07:44.500 --> 00:07:47.697
that shows that as you sleep at night,

00:07:47.697 --> 00:07:49.970
that's when those little dendritic spines

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:54.400
will like explode out and make
those synaptic connections.

00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:56.520
And it happens when you're sleeping.

00:07:56.520 --> 00:07:58.700
So if you've learned, you've studied,

00:07:58.700 --> 00:08:01.210
focused during the day,
you go to sleep at night,

00:08:01.210 --> 00:08:03.070
that's when the neural architecture

00:08:03.070 --> 00:08:05.770
is actually popping out and forming.

00:08:05.770 --> 00:08:07.690
So that's why sleep can be

00:08:07.690 --> 00:08:10.184
such an important part of learning.

00:08:10.184 --> 00:08:11.020
= And how do you know this?

00:08:11.020 --> 00:08:12.548
Have y'all actually looked at,

00:08:12.548 --> 00:08:14.870
do you have people trying
to learn something,

00:08:14.870 --> 00:08:17.408
and then you put 'em in
an MRI, how do you know?

00:08:17.408 --> 00:08:22.370
- Well Gwang Yang at NYU has
done some fantastic research

00:08:22.370 --> 00:08:25.958
published in science, and
it studies what happens

00:08:25.958 --> 00:08:28.710
to neurons when you sleep at night.

00:08:28.710 --> 00:08:31.130
And often some of these
studies involve mice

00:08:31.130 --> 00:08:35.780
because we don't want to
dissect little living infants

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:38.167
and so forth, for some reason.

00:08:38.167 --> 00:08:40.740
And but it's, but it really gives us

00:08:40.740 --> 00:08:43.390
a great understanding
of how that architecture

00:08:43.390 --> 00:08:45.060
is growing while we sleep.

00:08:45.060 --> 00:08:46.730
And there's another thing.

00:08:46.730 --> 00:08:49.400
When you go to sleep,
well, during the day,

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:51.660
as the day goes by, you get this sort of

00:08:51.660 --> 00:08:54.670
little toxic stuff that's
coming out of your cells.

00:08:54.670 --> 00:08:57.620
So that's why at night, you feel kind of

00:08:57.620 --> 00:08:59.210
mentally fatigued.

00:08:59.210 --> 00:09:01.380
But when you go to sleep, what happens is,

00:09:01.380 --> 00:09:03.530
your brain cells shrink.

00:09:03.530 --> 00:09:06.050
This allows those, the metabolic,

00:09:06.050 --> 00:09:09.150
I mean the sort of cerebral fluids

00:09:09.150 --> 00:09:11.900
to wash away those toxins and that's why

00:09:11.900 --> 00:09:14.230
in the morning you feel so much fresher.

00:09:14.230 --> 00:09:16.600
You don't wanna go a night without sleep

00:09:16.600 --> 00:09:18.640
or with a very small amount of sleep,

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:21.710
because that can't wash those toxins away,

00:09:21.710 --> 00:09:23.310
and then the next day, you're working

00:09:23.310 --> 00:09:26.370
with a poison brain,
which isn't a good idea.

00:09:26.370 --> 00:09:27.870
- So making this very tangible.

00:09:27.870 --> 00:09:31.585
If I have an exam coming
up, let's say next week,

00:09:31.585 --> 00:09:34.610
what would you, based on what you know,

00:09:34.610 --> 00:09:36.562
and based on what the science tells us,

00:09:36.562 --> 00:09:37.395
what would be the optimal strategy.

00:09:37.395 --> 00:09:39.080
And let's just say I don't know much

00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:41.010
of what is covered on the
exam in a week from now.

00:09:41.010 --> 00:09:44.440
How would you tell me to approach that?

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:46.414
- Don't sit there and
say, I'm gonna do 10 hours

00:09:46.414 --> 00:09:49.340
of studying the day before the exam.

00:09:49.340 --> 00:09:51.840
Instead, I'm going to take, let's say

00:09:51.840 --> 00:09:54.040
you have 10 hours available.

00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:57.462
Parse that out, do an hour,
hour and a half each day,

00:09:57.462 --> 00:09:59.884
and each day as you learning,

00:09:59.884 --> 00:10:02.100
that night when you go to sleep,

00:10:02.100 --> 00:10:03.624
you're making some more connections.

00:10:03.624 --> 00:10:06.380
The next night, you've studied some,

00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:07.900
and you're making more connections.

00:10:07.900 --> 00:10:10.800
And as each day goes by, you're building

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:13.370
a really solid set of connections.

00:10:13.370 --> 00:10:16.245
If you wait until the
day before and then cram,

00:10:16.245 --> 00:10:19.780
you're building very poor connections,

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:21.360
'cause you only have one night of sleep

00:10:21.360 --> 00:10:22.940
to actually do the connections with.

00:10:22.940 --> 00:10:23.933
- And sometimes, it's even worse.

00:10:23.933 --> 00:10:26.110
I remember from college,
what most students do

00:10:26.110 --> 00:10:27.831
is actually use that last night of sleep

00:10:27.831 --> 00:10:29.260
to study those 10 hours.

00:10:29.260 --> 00:10:32.580
And then they go in without
any sleep oftentimes.

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:34.290
Which sounds like the
worst possible thing.

00:10:34.290 --> 00:10:37.590
- It is, and then what sometimes happens

00:10:37.590 --> 00:10:38.740
is they'll come to me and say,

00:10:38.740 --> 00:10:41.110
I suffer from test anxiety.

00:10:41.110 --> 00:10:44.220
And actually, test anxiety is very real.

00:10:44.220 --> 00:10:46.160
Some people study really hard,

00:10:46.160 --> 00:10:47.970
and they get very nervous.

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:50.310
But other people use poor strategies,

00:10:50.310 --> 00:10:53.550
and then they freeze on the test,

00:10:53.550 --> 00:10:55.580
and it's because they didn't actually

00:10:55.580 --> 00:10:57.295
learn the material well.

00:10:57.295 --> 00:10:59.600
Because we don't teach about how

00:10:59.600 --> 00:11:01.740
the brain learns very much,

00:11:01.740 --> 00:11:04.674
that's part of why people
make these kinds of

00:11:04.674 --> 00:11:07.490
sometimes tragic mistakes.

00:11:07.490 --> 00:11:09.270
- So if this makes sense, and I think,

00:11:09.270 --> 00:11:11.030
even before knowing about the science,

00:11:11.030 --> 00:11:14.076
a lot of students, all
of us, intuitively know,

00:11:14.076 --> 00:11:16.900
yes, I should probably
start working on it sooner.

00:11:16.900 --> 00:11:18.470
I shouldn't do it last minute.

00:11:18.470 --> 00:11:20.740
So why do we, as humans, do that?

00:11:20.740 --> 00:11:22.750
Why do we put it off to the last minute?

00:11:22.750 --> 00:11:25.425
- Oh, because when you even
just think about something

00:11:25.425 --> 00:11:27.410
you don't like or don't want to do,

00:11:27.410 --> 00:11:29.460
it activates the insular cortex,

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:32.300
the portion of the brain
that experiences pain.

00:11:32.300 --> 00:11:34.790
So the brain naturally
enough skitters away

00:11:34.790 --> 00:11:36.740
from that thought to a new thought

00:11:36.740 --> 00:11:39.970
that's like, ooo, this
is so much more fun,

00:11:39.970 --> 00:11:42.180
and it'll go surfing the web

00:11:42.180 --> 00:11:44.040
or doing whatever's more fun,

00:11:44.040 --> 00:11:46.200
and you've just procrastinated.

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:50.860
So a very powerful way of
tackling this kind of thing

00:11:50.860 --> 00:11:53.266
is to use something called
the Pomodoro Technique,

00:11:53.266 --> 00:11:54.897
that was--
- Pomodoro?

00:11:54.897 --> 00:11:58.310
- Pomodoro, and that was
invented by an Italian,

00:11:58.310 --> 00:12:02.120
Francesco Cirillo, and
Pomodoro is Italian for tomato.

00:12:02.120 --> 00:12:03.490
It's so simple.

00:12:03.490 --> 00:12:05.750
What this does is it sneaks your brain

00:12:05.750 --> 00:12:10.660
past that tendency to go
away from whatever's painful.

00:12:10.660 --> 00:12:13.430
You just set a timer for 25 minutes,

00:12:13.430 --> 00:12:17.270
you get rid of anything
that's possibly a distraction.

00:12:17.270 --> 00:12:19.890
So no little ringy
dingies on your cell phone

00:12:19.890 --> 00:12:20.860
or that kind of thing,

00:12:20.860 --> 00:12:23.110
and no popups on your computer,

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:25.830
but then you set that
timer for 25 minutes,

00:12:25.830 --> 00:12:29.550
and you focus as intently
as you can for 25 minutes,

00:12:29.550 --> 00:12:31.730
realizing that we all, of course,

00:12:31.730 --> 00:12:36.470
have these monkey minds,
and you may catch yourself

00:12:36.470 --> 00:12:37.702
and have to bring yourself back,

00:12:37.702 --> 00:12:39.404
but the most important part,

00:12:39.404 --> 00:12:41.842
is when you're done with the 25 minutes,

00:12:41.842 --> 00:12:46.350
you relax, you reward
yourself with something.

00:12:46.350 --> 00:12:49.200
And what that's doing, is
that's actually allowing you

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:51.710
to get into the diffuse mode,

00:12:51.710 --> 00:12:54.410
this more task-negative, relaxing thing

00:12:54.410 --> 00:12:57.650
where you're consolidating
what you've just learned.

00:12:57.650 --> 00:13:01.883
So this is a big reason why
this technique is so powerful.

00:13:01.883 --> 00:13:05.210
- So, and is there something
magic about the 25 minutes?

00:13:05.210 --> 00:13:07.310
Why not 15 minutes or 40 minutes?

00:13:07.310 --> 00:13:09.720
- Oh, there is, very good question.

00:13:09.720 --> 00:13:14.030
So, the magic is that, remember
that pain in the brain?

00:13:14.030 --> 00:13:16.810
Well, it goes away after about 20 minutes.

00:13:16.810 --> 00:13:19.620
So 25 minutes is that perfect sweet spot

00:13:19.620 --> 00:13:21.730
that kind of starts
getting you in the flow,

00:13:21.730 --> 00:13:23.940
and you may even find, oh, wait,

00:13:23.940 --> 00:13:25.973
I'm at 25 minutes, it says I should stop,

00:13:25.973 --> 00:13:28.530
well, sometimes, I'm in the flow,

00:13:28.530 --> 00:13:31.030
so I'll just keep right on going.

00:13:31.030 --> 00:13:36.030
And that's okay if I go 25, 45, two hours,

00:13:36.270 --> 00:13:40.400
whenever, when I do stop, I reward myself,

00:13:40.400 --> 00:13:42.742
and that helps program my brain

00:13:42.742 --> 00:13:46.070
to enjoy the focusing process even more.

00:13:46.070 --> 00:13:47.700
It's like Pavlov with the dogs.

00:13:47.700 --> 00:13:50.940
He'd ring a bell and then after a while

00:13:50.940 --> 00:13:52.650
the dogs knew they were
gonna get a reward,

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:55.520
so they'd enjoy that time in between.

00:13:55.520 --> 00:13:57.290
We're even like that as humans.

00:13:57.290 --> 00:14:00.280
We can begin enjoying
that focusing period.

00:14:00.280 --> 00:14:02.827
- And so, make sure I understand,

00:14:03.817 --> 00:14:06.411
it's not that you have
to stop at 25 minutes.

00:14:06.411 --> 00:14:08.160
It's just that at 25
minutes, the bell rings,

00:14:08.160 --> 00:14:10.919
you have earned the right for guilt-free

00:14:10.919 --> 00:14:12.888
whatever it might be.

00:14:12.888 --> 00:14:13.900
- Bingo.
- Surfing the web,

00:14:13.900 --> 00:14:17.200
go for a walk, and that even
that time is still productive.

00:14:17.200 --> 00:14:18.610
You shouldn't have guilt
associated with it.

00:14:18.610 --> 00:14:20.130
One, you did your focused time,

00:14:20.130 --> 00:14:21.860
but you're also saying
you're getting into this,

00:14:21.860 --> 00:14:24.320
the default mode is how you described it,

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:27.527
and that's where your
brain, if you go for a walk,

00:14:27.527 --> 00:14:28.822
you're starting to form the connections

00:14:28.822 --> 00:14:29.655
based on what you just focused.

00:14:29.655 --> 00:14:30.993
- That's right, and we often think

00:14:30.993 --> 00:14:33.073
that if you're relaxing
and you're not focusing,

00:14:33.073 --> 00:14:34.600
that you're not doing any work.

00:14:34.600 --> 00:14:37.070
But actually, your brain is doing a lot

00:14:37.070 --> 00:14:39.800
of productive, yet subconscious, work

00:14:39.800 --> 00:14:41.340
when you're taking these breaks.

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:44.370
Which is part of why these
breaks are so important.

00:14:44.370 --> 00:14:48.549
And they also, if you focus,
focus, focus all the time,

00:14:48.549 --> 00:14:51.700
there is some evidence
that it might actually

00:14:51.700 --> 00:14:55.880
reduce your creativity, reduce the ability

00:14:55.880 --> 00:14:58.510
of the default mode to
kind of kick into play.

00:14:58.510 --> 00:15:00.640
So when you're taking these little breaks,

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:04.450
you're actually also sort of
encouraging your creativity.

00:15:04.450 --> 00:15:06.909
- And when the bell rings
but you're in your flow,

00:15:06.909 --> 00:15:09.100
and if you're getting,
if you're feeling like

00:15:09.100 --> 00:15:10.926
this is really good, and the pain,

00:15:10.926 --> 00:15:12.910
I mean, that is
fascinating, it's literally,

00:15:12.910 --> 00:15:14.580
'cause I don't feel physical pain.

00:15:14.580 --> 00:15:15.413
There's all sorts of things,

00:15:15.413 --> 00:15:17.060
I'm procrastinating at
least 20 things right now.

00:15:17.060 --> 00:15:19.800
And I'll, I don't feel pain,

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:23.180
but it's triggering the
same part of the brain.

00:15:23.180 --> 00:15:25.180
- Well, everybody procrastinates,

00:15:25.180 --> 00:15:26.870
because when you're working on one thing

00:15:26.870 --> 00:15:28.960
you're not working on another thing.

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:31.960
But you're a little bit, different,

00:15:31.960 --> 00:15:35.800
to use as a model case
for procrastination,

00:15:35.800 --> 00:15:38.360
because you don't think
like a lot of people do.

00:15:38.360 --> 00:15:39.470
But for me--

00:15:39.470 --> 00:15:40.722
- Probably a good thing.

00:15:40.722 --> 00:15:43.992
- But a lot of times you can get really,

00:15:43.992 --> 00:15:48.930
you can have a lot of good
things, good options on the table

00:15:48.930 --> 00:15:51.750
and then you may not feel
that pain in the brain.

00:15:51.750 --> 00:15:53.850
For me, usually there's something,

00:15:53.850 --> 00:15:56.090
I'll have this thing I wanna work on,

00:15:56.090 --> 00:15:57.590
this thing, this thing, this thing,

00:15:57.590 --> 00:15:59.480
and I'll work happily away,

00:15:59.480 --> 00:16:02.728
and there's this one thing,
and I've been putting it off,

00:16:02.728 --> 00:16:04.980
and that's the one that can kick in

00:16:04.980 --> 00:16:07.060
that pain in the brain sort of feeling.

00:16:07.060 --> 00:16:09.017
- And it's really, I mean,
you definitely avoid it,

00:16:09.017 --> 00:16:11.145
and it's like a subconscious pain almost.

00:16:11.145 --> 00:16:14.040
For just that point about this,

00:16:14.040 --> 00:16:16.277
I'm fascinated by this, the Pomodoro,

00:16:16.277 --> 00:16:18.860
and the timer, if you're
feeling in the flow.

00:16:18.860 --> 00:16:19.760
You don't have to stop.

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:21.380
You can keep going.

00:16:21.380 --> 00:16:23.180
- Yes, and what I'll often do,

00:16:23.180 --> 00:16:25.610
is I have a little timer on my computer,

00:16:25.610 --> 00:16:28.310
I'm using it, I'm working
away maybe on something,

00:16:28.310 --> 00:16:32.660
and I don't have my sound
turned on on the computer.

00:16:32.660 --> 00:16:34.800
So I can always just go check and see,

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:36.830
oh, has it expired or not?

00:16:36.830 --> 00:16:40.050
But it doesn't actually
kick me out and say,

00:16:40.050 --> 00:16:42.180
check, do you wanna quit now?

00:16:42.180 --> 00:16:46.140
I can just decide that when I feel free.

00:16:46.140 --> 00:16:47.872
But there's a lot of great apps

00:16:47.872 --> 00:16:50.600
using the Pomodoro Technique,

00:16:50.600 --> 00:16:54.070
so people like to use these
apps a lot of the time,

00:16:54.070 --> 00:16:56.020
and they'll collect Pomodoros.

00:16:56.020 --> 00:16:58.654
So Forest is a very popular app,

00:16:58.654 --> 00:17:03.510
and if you complete a
Pomodoro, you plant a tree.

00:17:03.510 --> 00:17:06.100
If you don't, you kill a tree.

00:17:06.100 --> 00:17:10.650
But you can collect like
two to three Pomodoros

00:17:10.650 --> 00:17:14.140
on a certain topic, another
number on another topic,

00:17:14.140 --> 00:17:15.292
if you like, if you're sort of,

00:17:15.292 --> 00:17:18.969
if that helps your productivity,

00:17:18.969 --> 00:17:20.700
it's a great approach.

00:17:20.700 --> 00:17:23.210
For me, I generally just love to work,

00:17:23.210 --> 00:17:24.950
so I'm working away, but occasionally,

00:17:24.950 --> 00:17:27.822
I will find myself surfing the web,

00:17:27.822 --> 00:17:30.361
and there's this one
thing I should be doing.

00:17:30.361 --> 00:17:33.080
So I'll set the timer and I'll get going

00:17:33.080 --> 00:17:35.100
with the Pomodoro, and I can feel it now.

00:17:35.100 --> 00:17:36.670
My brain is trained.

00:17:36.670 --> 00:17:40.550
As soon as I set that timer,
I start kind of working away

00:17:40.550 --> 00:17:42.060
and actually getting excited

00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:44.120
about even stuff I don't like.

00:17:44.120 --> 00:17:45.610
It's a great technique.

00:17:45.610 --> 00:17:47.350
- And there might be skeptics out there,

00:17:47.350 --> 00:17:50.950
says, okay, Professor
Oakley, she's saying it,

00:17:50.950 --> 00:17:52.390
but she's a fancy professor.

00:17:52.390 --> 00:17:55.862
You said, you know, my brain
might be wired differently,

00:17:55.862 --> 00:17:58.940
but they might say, your brain is probably

00:17:58.940 --> 00:17:59.773
wired differently.

00:17:59.773 --> 00:18:00.606
You're a professor.

00:18:00.606 --> 00:18:04.010
You've done, has this
always, how has learning

00:18:04.010 --> 00:18:06.300
been for you most of your life?

00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:08.380
- Well, before I talk about that,

00:18:08.380 --> 00:18:11.310
I should mention, so I
teach a very large course

00:18:11.310 --> 00:18:12.340
called Learning How to Learn

00:18:12.340 --> 00:18:14.358
with Terry Sejnowski on learning,

00:18:14.358 --> 00:18:17.919
and I have to say that out of

00:18:17.919 --> 00:18:20.620
two and a half million students,

00:18:20.620 --> 00:18:23.320
it almost seems sometimes
like I've heard from them all

00:18:23.320 --> 00:18:25.900
and they love the Pomodoro Technique.

00:18:25.900 --> 00:18:29.390
So it is, I've just
gotten a lot of feedback,

00:18:29.390 --> 00:18:31.520
and it really helps for everybody,

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:34.150
not just people like me.

00:18:34.150 --> 00:18:37.552
But people like me, well,
my own background is

00:18:37.552 --> 00:18:41.040
I hated math and science
when I was growing up.

00:18:41.040 --> 00:18:43.090
I flunked my way through
elementary, middle,

00:18:43.090 --> 00:18:44.460
and high school math and science.

00:18:44.460 --> 00:18:46.420
I just didn't have the math gene,

00:18:46.420 --> 00:18:47.799
knew I couldn't do it.

00:18:47.799 --> 00:18:51.150
And then when I was 26 years old,

00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:52.560
I was getting out of the military,

00:18:52.560 --> 00:18:55.440
and you know, for some weird reason,

00:18:55.440 --> 00:18:58.670
nobody wanted to get me
with my Slavic languages

00:18:58.670 --> 00:19:01.070
and literature degree, and I thought,

00:19:01.070 --> 00:19:04.740
maybe I should see if I
can learn something new,

00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:07.630
like maybe even this math stuff.

00:19:07.630 --> 00:19:10.386
Because I could see the
officers I'd worked with,

00:19:10.386 --> 00:19:12.850
they had great job opportunities,

00:19:12.850 --> 00:19:15.280
they were often West Point engineers,

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:19.400
and so I started, and see,

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:22.830
I wish there had been
Kahn Academy back then,

00:19:22.830 --> 00:19:25.450
but I started with remedial
high school algebra

00:19:25.450 --> 00:19:29.050
and started working my way
up, and now, and it worked.

00:19:29.050 --> 00:19:31.170
I'm a professor of engineering.

00:19:31.170 --> 00:19:36.170
But if you use some of
these ideas about learning,

00:19:36.293 --> 00:19:39.970
I've found that the way I learned Russian

00:19:39.970 --> 00:19:42.130
at the Defense Language Institute

00:19:42.130 --> 00:19:44.269
is actually very similar to how you learn

00:19:44.269 --> 00:19:47.933
in math and science, and when I applied

00:19:47.933 --> 00:19:50.930
those same techniques, which
are actually the techniques

00:19:50.930 --> 00:19:54.930
that involve how your brain
really learns, it worked.

00:19:54.930 --> 00:19:56.540
But if I'd known then what I know now

00:19:56.540 --> 00:19:59.110
about learning, I still
could've made it much easier.

00:19:59.110 --> 00:20:03.171
- So after the military, you went on this

00:20:03.171 --> 00:20:05.130
wanting to go back into math.

00:20:05.130 --> 00:20:07.150
But at that time, you did not
know about these techniques.

00:20:07.150 --> 00:20:08.760
You just, what was different about it

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:11.010
when you were learning it in your 20s

00:20:11.010 --> 00:20:12.370
versus when you first tried to learn it

00:20:12.370 --> 00:20:13.893
when you were 14 or 15.

00:20:14.900 --> 00:20:18.310
- I didn't have to have
a job when I was 14 or 15

00:20:18.310 --> 00:20:20.321
because I was supported by my parents.

00:20:20.321 --> 00:20:21.950
Yeah, I lived in that home.

00:20:21.950 --> 00:20:23.070
- So there was an urgency to it.

00:20:23.070 --> 00:20:25.090
There was a high stakes.

00:20:25.090 --> 00:20:27.710
- And I think part of it, too,

00:20:27.710 --> 00:20:30.332
is I looked at the future, and I thought,

00:20:30.332 --> 00:20:35.280
you know, we know language and culture

00:20:35.280 --> 00:20:37.710
is always gonna be really important,

00:20:37.710 --> 00:20:40.610
but in today's world, math and science

00:20:40.610 --> 00:20:42.720
is really important as well.

00:20:42.720 --> 00:20:46.260
And it's not like you
have to become an engineer

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:49.944
or a computer scientist, but
if you have some knowledge

00:20:49.944 --> 00:20:53.123
of those fields, it really
broadens your ability

00:20:53.123 --> 00:20:56.400
to get decent jobs today.

00:20:56.400 --> 00:20:59.770
So I always say, I did the
thing everybody told me,

00:20:59.770 --> 00:21:01.254
I followed my passion.

00:21:01.254 --> 00:21:02.480
I learned a language.

00:21:02.480 --> 00:21:06.100
But I didn't broaden my passion.

00:21:06.100 --> 00:21:08.030
And that left me in a box.

00:21:08.030 --> 00:21:10.611
And so today, I often encourage people,

00:21:10.611 --> 00:21:13.560
it's great to follow your passion,

00:21:13.560 --> 00:21:17.310
but broaden it also, and
you'll find that it's

00:21:17.310 --> 00:21:20.010
really helpful in today's working world.

00:21:20.010 --> 00:21:24.660
- And how did you, so
you went back into math,

00:21:24.660 --> 00:21:26.828
motivated, to some degree, by economics,

00:21:26.828 --> 00:21:29.680
and you, it seems like you learned it.

00:21:29.680 --> 00:21:32.260
How did you fall into
this area of research?

00:21:32.260 --> 00:21:35.400
When you went back to grad school,

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:38.590
did you say, I want, this
learning is interesting to me

00:21:38.590 --> 00:21:40.390
because it, there's a phase in my life

00:21:40.390 --> 00:21:42.640
where I had trouble and
now I figured it out?

00:21:42.640 --> 00:21:44.440
Or did you, how did you get to this field,

00:21:44.440 --> 00:21:45.680
which is a fascinating one?

00:21:45.680 --> 00:21:47.340
I think it applies to everyone.

00:21:47.340 --> 00:21:49.300
What was the trigger
that got you interested?

00:21:49.300 --> 00:21:50.540
- Oh, good question.

00:21:50.540 --> 00:21:54.380
So I did kind of just dink
around a lot in my life.

00:21:54.380 --> 00:21:56.980
I mean, I was in the military as enlisted

00:21:56.980 --> 00:21:59.550
and an officer, I worked
at the South Pole Station

00:21:59.550 --> 00:22:00.707
in Antarctica--

00:22:01.569 --> 00:22:04.053
- [Sal] Wouldn't categorize
that as dinking around.

00:22:04.053 --> 00:22:07.320
That seems, that's kind of
hard core dinking, I guess.

00:22:07.320 --> 00:22:08.540
- Yes, hard core.
- That's quite

00:22:08.540 --> 00:22:09.547
impressive dinking.
(audience laughter)

00:22:09.547 --> 00:22:12.935
- And I used to work as a translator

00:22:12.935 --> 00:22:17.176
for the Russians on Soviet
trawlers up in the Bering Sea.

00:22:17.176 --> 00:22:20.566
But in all of these kinds of things,

00:22:20.566 --> 00:22:24.120
now, see, there's one problem, though.

00:22:24.120 --> 00:22:25.830
See, I'm not like you.

00:22:25.830 --> 00:22:28.130
You have this incredible working memory.

00:22:28.130 --> 00:22:31.780
My working memory is
like one thing at a time,

00:22:31.780 --> 00:22:34.270
and when get on, I get
it, and it's like, so,

00:22:34.270 --> 00:22:36.560
Ooo, it's shiny, and
then I get distracted--

00:22:36.560 --> 00:22:38.052
- [Sal] We are more
similar than you imagine.

00:22:38.052 --> 00:22:41.240
- So what was the question again?

00:22:41.240 --> 00:22:44.630
- For real?

00:22:44.630 --> 00:22:46.944
- For real.
(audience laughter)

00:22:46.944 --> 00:22:48.433
- Oh, yeah, no, that's,
I thought that was,

00:22:48.433 --> 00:22:49.266
how did you get interested?

00:22:49.266 --> 00:22:51.140
Maybe I do have slightly
longer working memory,

00:22:51.140 --> 00:22:52.990
if that was for real.

00:22:52.990 --> 00:22:55.403
But how did you get
interested in this field?

00:22:56.410 --> 00:22:59.503
- The thing is, I, well,

00:23:00.880 --> 00:23:04.230
it just, a student asked
a question, and said,

00:23:04.230 --> 00:23:06.949
he found out, 'cause I was
just a typical professor,

00:23:06.949 --> 00:23:11.237
maybe with a little bit
lower working memory

00:23:11.237 --> 00:23:13.270
than many professors,

00:23:13.270 --> 00:23:16.960
but I did my engineering
research and so forth.

00:23:16.960 --> 00:23:19.430
And one day, but I loved to write.

00:23:19.430 --> 00:23:20.850
And so on the side, I'd write,

00:23:20.850 --> 00:23:22.990
but I'd keep it hidden because tenure,

00:23:22.990 --> 00:23:23.900
and all that kind of stuff.

00:23:23.900 --> 00:23:28.010
So one day a student asked me,

00:23:28.010 --> 00:23:30.410
he found out I was terrible
at math growing up,

00:23:30.410 --> 00:23:32.950
and said, you know, how'd you do it?

00:23:32.950 --> 00:23:34.300
How'd you change your brain?

00:23:34.300 --> 00:23:37.350
And I thought, how did I change my brain?

00:23:37.350 --> 00:23:39.460
And so I wrote him a little email,

00:23:39.460 --> 00:23:42.213
and then I thought, well,
because of the past books

00:23:42.213 --> 00:23:45.870
I'd written, I knew a
little about neuroscience,

00:23:45.870 --> 00:23:47.570
about cognitive psychology.

00:23:47.570 --> 00:23:50.540
And I thought, well, I should put together

00:23:50.540 --> 00:23:53.150
some of these ideas,
because a lot of information

00:23:53.150 --> 00:23:56.106
that's out there on learning
comes from education

00:23:56.106 --> 00:23:59.060
or some from the field
of cognitive psychology,

00:23:59.060 --> 00:24:01.610
but there's actually all
this incredible research

00:24:01.610 --> 00:24:03.780
that's being done in the
field of neuroscience.

00:24:03.780 --> 00:24:08.780
And so I put together a manuscript,

00:24:09.820 --> 00:24:12.882
and that became the
book, A Mind for Numbers.

00:24:12.882 --> 00:24:15.790
I just kinda wrote a book about it

00:24:15.790 --> 00:24:18.410
and it turned out really super popular,

00:24:18.410 --> 00:24:21.500
and so I was just surprised.

00:24:21.500 --> 00:24:24.698
'Cause it was kind of a
little side venture for me

00:24:24.698 --> 00:24:26.930
because I just thought I was gonna do

00:24:26.930 --> 00:24:28.580
my normal engineering stuff,

00:24:28.580 --> 00:24:31.110
and then people really liked it.

00:24:31.110 --> 00:24:33.480
It was a very fresh approach,
I think, to learning

00:24:33.480 --> 00:24:35.820
that brought in, a lot of times,

00:24:35.820 --> 00:24:38.880
what, there's great, great information

00:24:38.880 --> 00:24:40.763
about how to learn effectively,

00:24:40.763 --> 00:24:44.080
but it really only
encompasses a small portion

00:24:44.080 --> 00:24:47.840
of what is truly needed to
know how to learn effectively.

00:24:47.840 --> 00:24:50.973
So, for example, you
find these great books

00:24:50.973 --> 00:24:54.205
in cognitive psychology
and they don't even mention

00:24:54.205 --> 00:24:57.630
that procrastination
is the number one issue

00:24:57.630 --> 00:24:59.584
for students and how do you tackle that?

00:24:59.584 --> 00:25:02.660
And there's just so much information

00:25:02.660 --> 00:25:04.760
that's not being put together,

00:25:04.760 --> 00:25:09.720
and so I like to synthesize
and stand on the shoulders

00:25:09.720 --> 00:25:12.380
of these great researchers, but bring in

00:25:12.380 --> 00:25:15.507
a lot of different ideas, and so that's,

00:25:15.507 --> 00:25:18.420
I just kind of backed
into it accidentally.

00:25:18.420 --> 00:25:19.740
- 'Cause it is fascinating,
'cause there is

00:25:19.740 --> 00:25:21.630
all this research going on that I actually

00:25:21.630 --> 00:25:23.670
had no idea about until starting to look

00:25:23.670 --> 00:25:26.820
at some of your work,
and it is so practical,

00:25:26.820 --> 00:25:29.483
and it so relevant to frankly everyone,

00:25:29.483 --> 00:25:31.720
but no one was really communicating,

00:25:31.720 --> 00:25:34.410
or maybe, communicating
it in the right way.

00:25:34.410 --> 00:25:39.240
Why isn't this part of, why
doesn't every orientation

00:25:39.240 --> 00:25:41.570
at every school and college and workplace

00:25:41.570 --> 00:25:43.430
start off with these techniques?

00:25:43.430 --> 00:25:44.930
'Cause it seems like,
it's not just school,

00:25:44.930 --> 00:25:47.090
it seems like even in
the workplace, you know,

00:25:47.090 --> 00:25:48.850
there's I gotta get that memo

00:25:48.850 --> 00:25:51.860
out to my coworker by Wednesday.

00:25:51.860 --> 00:25:53.454
I go, I'll do it Tuesday night.

00:25:53.454 --> 00:25:57.250
Why isn't this more
widespread in your sense?

00:25:57.250 --> 00:26:01.410
- I think that it's, it's really only

00:26:01.410 --> 00:26:03.070
in the last 10 years or so

00:26:03.070 --> 00:26:05.810
that we have gotten a good understanding

00:26:05.810 --> 00:26:07.554
of how the brain works,
or a better understanding.

00:26:07.554 --> 00:26:09.610
There's still a long way to go.

00:26:09.610 --> 00:26:13.140
And it hasn't caught up
with modern pedagogy,

00:26:13.140 --> 00:26:16.230
and so if you asked,
let's say you ask someone

00:26:16.230 --> 00:26:19.350
to create an online course on
how do you learn effectively,

00:26:19.350 --> 00:26:22.580
or you ask some university,
a major university,

00:26:22.580 --> 00:26:24.000
to produce such a course.

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:26.820
They'd say great, we'll
do it for teachers.

00:26:26.820 --> 00:26:29.410
And if you said, no,
actually, normal people,

00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:31.340
ordinary people would
like to know this, too.

00:26:31.340 --> 00:26:33.500
They'd say, good, we'll produce a course

00:26:33.500 --> 00:26:36.150
and it will have two weeks
on the history of education,

00:26:36.150 --> 00:26:37.928
two more weeks on theories of education,

00:26:37.928 --> 00:26:39.919
two more weeks on how babies learn,

00:26:39.919 --> 00:26:42.610
a little bit on how people learn,

00:26:42.610 --> 00:26:45.030
but no neuroscience,
maybe just one lecture,

00:26:45.030 --> 00:26:46.203
'cause it's too hard.

00:26:47.230 --> 00:26:49.890
So what Terry and I did was kind of flip

00:26:49.890 --> 00:26:51.466
that all on its head and say,

00:26:51.466 --> 00:26:53.850
well, let's start from neuroscience.

00:26:53.850 --> 00:26:56.110
If it's too advanced,
we'll use some metaphors

00:26:56.110 --> 00:26:57.440
to help bring you along.

00:26:57.440 --> 00:27:00.590
And it actually is easy stuff,

00:27:00.590 --> 00:27:02.880
and it's so useful, and that's why

00:27:02.880 --> 00:27:06.810
the Learning How to Learn
course is so incredibly popular.

00:27:06.810 --> 00:27:10.780
It's simple and easy kinds of information,

00:27:10.780 --> 00:27:12.560
but I think some of it, too,

00:27:12.560 --> 00:27:17.170
is let's say you are a professor
of cognitive psychology

00:27:17.170 --> 00:27:20.040
and you've just spent the
last 30 years of your life

00:27:20.040 --> 00:27:22.906
researching issues
related to working memory,

00:27:22.906 --> 00:27:26.064
you know, there's part
of you that screams,

00:27:26.064 --> 00:27:29.200
well, it can't be that easy.

00:27:29.200 --> 00:27:31.780
You know, I've been working
forever on this thing

00:27:31.780 --> 00:27:33.600
and she's making it just like,

00:27:33.600 --> 00:27:37.110
but it actually is, the fundamental ideas

00:27:37.110 --> 00:27:40.980
are really, really easy
for anybody to understand.

00:27:40.980 --> 00:27:43.971
And so, I've been working with Terry

00:27:43.971 --> 00:27:48.971
and Greg Hammons to make some
great videos for kids now

00:27:49.370 --> 00:27:52.130
that also explain some of these ideas,

00:27:52.130 --> 00:27:54.590
because everybody says,
these ideas about learning

00:27:54.590 --> 00:27:57.550
are so simple that anybody can learn 'em.

00:27:57.550 --> 00:27:59.760
I wish I had known them when I was a kid.

00:27:59.760 --> 00:28:01.950
Actually, that's true, so that's what

00:28:01.950 --> 00:28:03.280
we've been working on.

00:28:03.280 --> 00:28:05.377
- Yeah, it's so surprising, because one,

00:28:05.377 --> 00:28:08.160
they seem, they make intuitive sense,

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:09.640
but then when you back it up

00:28:09.640 --> 00:28:11.690
with the neuroscience, then it...

00:28:11.690 --> 00:28:12.880
Are there skeptics here?

00:28:12.880 --> 00:28:14.760
It feels like you could
say the sky is blue

00:28:14.760 --> 00:28:15.593
and there'll be skeptics.

00:28:15.593 --> 00:28:17.323
There'll be someone who will say,

00:28:17.323 --> 00:28:18.850
are there people who say, well, no,

00:28:18.850 --> 00:28:20.430
that's not exactly right,

00:28:20.430 --> 00:28:22.987
sometimes it's better to pull
an all-nighter, I don't know.

00:28:22.987 --> 00:28:25.223
Are you hearing push back from anyone?

00:28:27.439 --> 00:28:30.723
- No, I mean, every great
once in a while, you get,

00:28:30.723 --> 00:28:33.360
anybody will get push back.

00:28:33.360 --> 00:28:35.570
But, when you're working with

00:28:35.570 --> 00:28:38.035
one of the world's
greatest neuroscientists,

00:28:38.035 --> 00:28:40.113
all I kinda have to do is say,

00:28:40.113 --> 00:28:42.270
okay, you wanna argue
about the neuroscience?

00:28:42.270 --> 00:28:43.460
Go talk to this guy.

00:28:43.460 --> 00:28:47.897
And Terry is really one
of the world leaders.

00:28:47.897 --> 00:28:52.897
I think if you use a metaphorical approach

00:28:52.950 --> 00:28:55.710
to explain some of
these fundamental ideas,

00:28:55.710 --> 00:28:59.083
and you say, I'm using a
metaphor, this is the main idea,

00:28:59.083 --> 00:29:02.913
it's kind of hard to argue with that.

