00:54:28.040 --> 00:54:29.815
but as much as you can,
try to keep your focus

00:54:29.815 --> 00:54:32.328
'cause the longer you're on there,

00:54:32.328 --> 00:54:36.590
the deeper, it's like you're
building these networks,

00:54:36.590 --> 00:54:38.519
this connection, you're
bringing it all to mind,

00:54:38.519 --> 00:54:43.500
and you wanna just keep
that without multitasking.

00:54:43.500 --> 00:54:46.010
'Cause if you're going to another task,

00:54:46.010 --> 00:54:48.460
it's like you're ripping
out of those neurons,

00:54:48.460 --> 00:54:50.614
and now you're going to
another set of neurons,

00:54:50.614 --> 00:54:53.840
and then you've gotta go back to that set

00:54:53.840 --> 00:54:56.880
of original neurons and
that can be really tiring.

00:54:56.880 --> 00:54:58.450
So hopefully this might help.

00:54:58.450 --> 00:55:00.770
- Is there a, we talk
about the 25 minutes.

00:55:00.770 --> 00:55:02.360
We don't wanna get too prescriptive,

00:55:02.360 --> 00:55:05.180
but is there a sense of
how long the diffuse time,

00:55:05.180 --> 00:55:07.910
is there a ratio that
people think is good?

00:55:07.910 --> 00:55:09.650
- This is not studied enough.

00:55:09.650 --> 00:55:12.190
What I just hear anecdotally is,

00:55:12.190 --> 00:55:14.320
if you have a fair bit of work to do,

00:55:14.320 --> 00:55:17.340
then maybe five to 10
minutes, something like that.

00:55:17.340 --> 00:55:19.515
If you have trouble getting
yourself back on task

00:55:19.515 --> 00:55:24.090
after you're taking a break,
set a timer for the break.

00:55:24.090 --> 00:55:26.320
Some people like to have a timer

00:55:26.320 --> 00:55:29.250
that's a ticking timer when
they're doing their Pomodoro

00:55:29.250 --> 00:55:32.250
because it helps remind
them to keep on task.

00:55:32.250 --> 00:55:36.400
For me, I like silence when I'm doing it.

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:40.130
But five to 10 minutes,
and then after you've done

00:55:40.130 --> 00:55:43.100
several in row, then maybe
take a 15 minute break.

00:55:43.100 --> 00:55:45.410
- 25 minutes on, five to 10 minutes off.

00:55:45.410 --> 00:55:47.023
It would speak to Grishawn's question,

00:55:47.023 --> 00:55:49.850
you know, we have a lab school downstairs,

00:55:49.850 --> 00:55:51.970
and one of the goals
of it is to think about

00:55:51.970 --> 00:55:53.560
what school should be like.

00:55:53.560 --> 00:55:56.060
And so even this technique,
and we already have

00:55:56.060 --> 00:55:58.184
a principle around as much
active learning as possible

00:55:58.184 --> 00:56:00.715
versus passive learning, but
even that active learning,

00:56:00.715 --> 00:56:03.250
we might have to get
everyone timers or something

00:56:03.250 --> 00:56:05.340
to think about how to do this,

00:56:05.340 --> 00:56:07.450
followed by maybe 10, 15 minutes breaks

00:56:07.450 --> 00:56:09.109
could be interesting.

00:56:09.109 --> 00:56:11.707
- And I had to point out, when
it comes to active learning,

00:56:11.707 --> 00:56:14.440
there's a large
meta-analysis that was done

00:56:14.440 --> 00:56:17.990
of STEM learning, and what they found was

00:56:17.990 --> 00:56:21.250
that one in three students would

00:56:21.250 --> 00:56:22.720
drop out of STEM programs,

00:56:22.720 --> 00:56:24.530
science, technology,
engineering, and math,

00:56:24.530 --> 00:56:27.290
if it was just the traditionally taught.

00:56:27.290 --> 00:56:29.240
But only one in five would drop out

00:56:29.240 --> 00:56:30.750
if it was active learning.

00:56:30.750 --> 00:56:34.220
And part of what's
going on, I think of it,

00:56:34.220 --> 00:56:36.010
and I think there's some truth to this,

00:56:36.010 --> 00:56:38.520
is when you're active learning,

00:56:38.520 --> 00:56:42.760
you're not not just
passively watching someone.

00:56:42.760 --> 00:56:47.235
You are, in some sense,
like here's your dendrite

00:56:47.235 --> 00:56:52.235
on your neuron, you are almost
pulling a dendritic spine

00:56:52.290 --> 00:56:55.490
to start coming out and
making a little connection.

00:56:55.490 --> 00:56:57.775
And that's what active,
that's almost, I think,

00:56:57.775 --> 00:57:01.709
and maybe studies will
show this, we'll see,

00:57:01.709 --> 00:57:05.360
but that's almost why
when you're really working

00:57:05.360 --> 00:57:07.647
on something hard with
deliberate practice,

00:57:07.647 --> 00:57:09.423
it almost hurts.

00:57:10.637 --> 00:57:15.576
So I can relate this to why I
cannot play the piano today.

00:57:15.576 --> 00:57:19.448
So when my parents wanted
me to play the piano,

00:57:19.448 --> 00:57:24.448
so I found out, though,
I was not a dumb kid,

00:57:24.670 --> 00:57:27.980
I found out that as
long as you were hearing

00:57:27.980 --> 00:57:32.130
music come out, they didn't
mind whatever I was doing.

00:57:32.130 --> 00:57:34.626
So I learned a song,
and I played that song

00:57:34.626 --> 00:57:39.626
over and over, I put a comic book up,

00:57:39.710 --> 00:57:41.730
and I could just play
that song over and over

00:57:41.730 --> 00:57:44.840
for an hour while I was
reading my comic book,

00:57:44.840 --> 00:57:46.580
and I could read my comic book--

00:57:46.580 --> 00:57:48.690
- [Sal] That's actually quite impressive.

00:57:48.690 --> 00:57:51.250
- If you learn a song really well,

00:57:51.250 --> 00:57:54.220
but did I advance in my studies?

00:57:54.220 --> 00:57:57.020
No, I didn't, because I wasn't
doing deliberate practice.

00:57:57.020 --> 00:57:59.525
I wasn't pushing myself beyond,

00:57:59.525 --> 00:58:04.525
and so that is the essence
of why deliberate practice,

00:58:06.010 --> 00:58:08.550
kind of focusing on the harder stuff--

00:58:08.550 --> 00:58:09.970
- A little bit out of your comfort zone,

00:58:09.970 --> 00:58:12.317
stretching a little bit,
zone of proximal development,

00:58:12.317 --> 00:58:14.940
Goldilocks zone, whatever people call it.

00:58:14.940 --> 00:58:16.100
You did not do that.

00:58:16.100 --> 00:58:20.010
- I did not do that, and
now I cannot play the piano.

00:58:20.010 --> 00:58:21.723
